# Getting Started

From an empty directory to a themed, rendering element. Drip
vendors elements as source, so setup is a few files you can read rather than a
toolchain you configure.

> **Preview Release.** The elements and default theme are pre-1.0 and still settling; theme token names may change before then. Because elements are vendored as source, nothing you have already added moves under you.

## Create a Lustre Project

Drip expects a Lustre project served by `lustre_dev_tools`. If you're starting fresh, scaffold one:

```sh
gleam new my_app
cd my_app
gleam add lustre
gleam add lustre_dev_tools --dev
```

## Install Drip

Drip is a dev dependency that writes files into your project and stays out of your bundle.

```sh
gleam add drip --dev
```

## Initialize the Project

From the project root:

```sh
gleam run -m drip -- init
```

init writes three files.

- `src/ui/theme.css` holds the design tokens, every CSS variable the elements draw from.
- `src/ui/index.css` imports the theme and every element stylesheet. add and remove regenerate this file from the elements on disk.
- `src/my_app.css` is the entry stylesheet, named after your package so `lustre_dev_tools` discovers it. It pulls in Tailwind and the index, then stays put.

The entry stylesheet is where the build hooks in. It stays two lines:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@import "./ui/index.css";
```

The Tailwind import has to stay here: `lustre_dev_tools` only looks for it in the entry stylesheet, not in the files it imports. If the file already exists, init adds whichever of the two imports is missing and leaves the rest of your styles alone.

Right after init the index just imports the theme:

```css
/* Generated by drip; do not edit. Run drip add / drip remove to change it. */
@import "./theme.css";
```

Drip generates this file from the elements on disk, so add and remove keep it in sync, one import per element. You never edit it by hand; your own styles belong in the entry stylesheet.

Pass `--prefix=<name>` to vendor elements under a different directory name; init records it in the `[tools.drip]` table of your `gleam.toml` so every later command follows it.

## Add Your First Element

Vendor a button:

```sh
gleam run -m drip -- add button
```

The element's module and stylesheet land in `src/ui`, and the index is regenerated to import the stylesheet. Dependencies come automatically: `add field` brings separator with it.

## Render It

Import the element and use it in a view.

```gleam
import lustre
import lustre/element.{type Element}
import lustre/element/html
import ui/button

pub fn main() -> Nil {
  let app = lustre.element(view())
  let assert Ok(_) = lustre.start(app, "#app", Nil)
  Nil
}

fn view() -> Element(message) {
  button.button([button.accent()], [html.text("Hello, drip")])
}
```

Every element renders to an ordinary Lustre element. No providers, no context, no wrapper to mount: your view stays a pure function of state.

## Start the Dev Server

One command compiles and serves the app:

```sh
gleam run -m lustre/dev start
```

Open the printed address and the button renders with its styles applied. There is no separate Tailwind step: `lustre_dev_tools` picks up the import in the entry stylesheet and compiles the CSS as part of the build.

## Make It Yours

Every color, radius, and typeface the elements use routes through the variables in `src/ui/theme.css`. Both palettes live there, light and dark. Edit the file like any other code you own. The theming guide walks through every token, dark mode, and the radius scale.

## Icons

Drip ships no icon library. The examples on this site, and the few elements that carry an icon of their own (the accordion chevron, the checkbox check, and so on), all route through a single `ui/icon` module, so their calls read `icon.arrow_right([])`.

Recreate that module with any icon set you like: an icon is just a function that returns an element. The quickest route is `lucide_lustre`, which ships the icons this site uses and writes the module for you:

```sh
gleam add lucide_lustre@2 --dev

# every icon, written to src/ui/icon.gleam
gleam run -m lucide_lustre/add_all ui/icon

# or just the ones you use
gleam run -m lucide_lustre/add arrow_right ui/icon
```

Then `import ui/icon` and call icons the way the examples do. `lucide_lustre` draws Lucide's default stroke, a touch heavier than the one this site uses, so nudge `stroke-width` if you want a pixel-perfect match.

## Manual Setup

The CLI is a convenience, not a requirement. Every element page prints its full source under the Manual tab of its Installation section, so you can vendor elements by hand and skip the dev dependency entirely. The scaffolding is the same three files init writes:

- `src/my_app.css` is the two-line entry stylesheet shown under Initialize the Project, named after your package so `lustre_dev_tools` discovers it.
- `src/ui/theme.css` holds the design tokens. Copy the default theme from the theming guide, which prints the file in full.
- `src/ui/index.css` imports the theme ahead of every element stylesheet. Without the CLI to regenerate it, the file is yours to maintain.

After vendoring a button, the index reads:

```css
@import "./theme.css";
@import "./button.css";
```

From there every element is the same two moves: drop the files from its Manual tab into `src/ui/`, and add the stylesheet's `@import` line to the index. When an element builds on others, the Manual tab names them; vendor those the same way.

## Next Steps

The introduction makes the case for owning your elements; the catalog shows everything you can add; and the CLI reference covers every command.

